<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-18T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-18T09:00:00-05:00" n="1071" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1071">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.943 Manchuria/31: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-18T23:00:00+09:00">November 18, 1937—11
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 18—10:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>551. The British Consul General in Mukden has been instructed to protest
                            to the Manchukuo authorities against the Japanese unilateral surrender
                            of extraterritoriality and to make clear that Great Britain does not
                            recognize such surrender as applying to British subjects. All treaty
                            rights are reserved. Craigie<note n="57" xml:id="d1071fn57">Sir Robert
                                L. Craigie, British Ambassador in Japan.</note> is to make a similar
                            reservation here. I hope shortly to be able to cable the text or summary
                            of the British note.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>